Title: The Value of Free Water: Analyzing South Africa's Free Basic Water Policy 
Author-Name: Andrea Szabó  
Abstract:
  This paper analyzes South Africa's Free Basic Water Policy, under which
 households receive a free water allowance equal to the World Health
 Organization's recommended minimum. I estimate residential water demand,
 evaluate the welfare effects of free water, and provide optimal price
 schedules derived from a social planner's problem. I use a data set of
 monthly metered billing data for 60,000 households for 2002–2009 from a
 particularly disadvantaged suburb of Pretoria, with rich price variation
 across 20 different nonlinear tariff schedules. I find that the free
 allowance acts as a lump‐sum subsidy, without large effects on water
 consumption. However, it is possible to reallocate the current subsidy to
 form an optimal tariff without a free allowance, which would increase
 welfare while leaving the water provider's profit unchanged. This optimal
 tariff would also reduce the number of households consuming low quantities
 of water, a desirable policy goal according to the WHO. 
